Here's a minimal API endpoint handling multipart form uploads with multiple images and a description:

```csharp
// Program.cs

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Raise the max request body size (default is ~30MB)
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o => o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 50 * 1024 * 1024);

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (IFormFileCollection files, HttpRequest request) =>
{
    var description = request.Form["description"].ToString();

    if (files.Count == 0)
        return Results.BadRequest("No files uploaded.");

    var allowed = new[] { "image/jpeg", "image/png", "image/webp", "image/gif" };
    var saved = new List<string>();

    foreach (var file in files)
    {
        if (!allowed.Contains(file.ContentType))
            return Results.BadRequest($"Invalid content type: {file.ContentType}");

        var dest = Path.Combine("uploads", $"{Guid.NewGuid()}{Path.GetExtension(file.FileName)}");
        Directory.CreateDirectory("uploads");

        await using var stream = File.Create(dest);
        await file.CopyToAsync(stream);
        saved.Add(dest);
    }

    return Results.Ok(new { description, fileCount = saved.Count, paths = saved });
})
.DisableAntiforgery()                          // required for minimal APIs accepting forms
.Accepts<IFormFileCollection>("multipart/form-data");

app.Run();
```

**Key points:**

- **`IFormFileCollection`** binds all files from the form; the text field is read from `request.Form["description"]`.
- **`ConfigureKestrel`** raises the body limit to 50 MB. If you're behind IIS/Nginx, raise it there too (`maxAllowedContentLength` / `client_max_body_size`).
- **`.DisableAntiforgery()`** is needed in .NET 8 — without it, form POSTs return 400 by default.
- Content-type validation prevents non-image uploads.

**Test with curl:**

```bash
curl -X POST http://localhost:5000/upload \
  -F "files=@photo1.jpg" \
  -F "files=@photo2.png" \
  -F "description=Vacation pics"
```
